</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Although delayed contrast material–enhanced cardiac magnetic resonance (MR) imaging has traditionally been used to evaluate ischemic disease and myocardial viability, it is increasingly being used in the evaluation of nonischemic cardiomyopathies. Unlike myocardial infarction, which demonstrates subendocardial or transmural delayed contrast enhancement in a vascular distribution, nonischemic cardiomyopathies demonstrate enhancement that is not limited to a vascular territory. In combination with other cardiac MR imaging features, the location (subendocardial, transmural, subepicardial, or mesocardial) and pattern (patchy or diffuse) of abnormal delayed myocardial enhancement allow differentiation between ischemic (infarct-related) and nonischemic cardiomyopathies and, in cases of nonischemic cardiomyopathy, narrowing of the differential diagnosis. With use of a structured approach, delayed contrast-enhanced cardiac MR imaging can be helpful in the early detection and appropriate treatment of nonischemic cardiomyopathies.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.291085052">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.291085052">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g01a.jpeg" height="1527" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1a.</b>  Subendocardial infarction in a 46-year-old man who presented with recurrent chest pain. Occlusion of the left anterior descending coronary artery was seen at cardiac catheterization performed 2 years earlier. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis cardiac MR images obtained from the base <b>(a)</b> toward the apex <b>(c)</b> show subendocardial enhancement in the anteroseptal and anterior walls (arrow), a finding that is consistent with a nontransmural infarct in the distribution of the left anterior descending coronary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F1A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g01b.jpeg" height="1540" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1b.</b>  Subendocardial infarction in a 46-year-old man who presented with recurrent chest pain. Occlusion of the left anterior descending coronary artery was seen at cardiac catheterization performed 2 years earlier. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis cardiac MR images obtained from the base <b>(a)</b> toward the apex <b>(c)</b> show subendocardial enhancement in the anteroseptal and anterior walls (arrow), a finding that is consistent with a nontransmural infarct in the distribution of the left anterior descending coronary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F1B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g01c.jpeg" height="1540" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1c.</b>  Subendocardial infarction in a 46-year-old man who presented with recurrent chest pain. Occlusion of the left anterior descending coronary artery was seen at cardiac catheterization performed 2 years earlier. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis cardiac MR images obtained from the base <b>(a)</b> toward the apex <b>(c)</b> show subendocardial enhancement in the anteroseptal and anterior walls (arrow), a finding that is consistent with a nontransmural infarct in the distribution of the left anterior descending coronary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F1C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g02a.jpeg" height="1583" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  Cardiac amyloidosis in a 54-year-old man with multiple myeloma and known systemic amyloidosis who presented with congestive heart failure. <b>(a, b)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis cardiac MR images show diffuse subendocardial enhancement (arrows) that is not limited to a vascular distribution, along with the absence of blood pool enhancement, findings that are characteristic of cardiac amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Coronal half-Fourier acquisition single-shot turbo spin-echo image shows T2 hyperintense pulmonary and hepatic nodules (arrows), findings that represent extracardiac amyloid deposition.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g02b.jpeg" height="1618" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  Cardiac amyloidosis in a 54-year-old man with multiple myeloma and known systemic amyloidosis who presented with congestive heart failure. <b>(a, b)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis cardiac MR images show diffuse subendocardial enhancement (arrows) that is not limited to a vascular distribution, along with the absence of blood pool enhancement, findings that are characteristic of cardiac amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Coronal half-Fourier acquisition single-shot turbo spin-echo image shows T2 hyperintense pulmonary and hepatic nodules (arrows), findings that represent extracardiac amyloid deposition.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g02c.jpeg" height="1542" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2c.</b>  Cardiac amyloidosis in a 54-year-old man with multiple myeloma and known systemic amyloidosis who presented with congestive heart failure. <b>(a, b)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis cardiac MR images show diffuse subendocardial enhancement (arrows) that is not limited to a vascular distribution, along with the absence of blood pool enhancement, findings that are characteristic of cardiac amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Coronal half-Fourier acquisition single-shot turbo spin-echo image shows T2 hyperintense pulmonary and hepatic nodules (arrows), findings that represent extracardiac amyloid deposition.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F2C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g03a.jpeg" height="1600" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3a.</b>  Cardiac amyloidosis in a 75-year-old man with multiple myeloma. Diffuse myocardial thickening and restrictive physiologic findings were seen at cardiac echocardiography. <b>(a)</b> Two-chamber short-axis true fast imaging with steady-state precession (FISP) image shows bilateral ventricular myocardial thickening. <b>(b, c)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced two-chamber short-axis cardiac MR images (<b>c</b> obtained slightly apical to <b>b</b>) show apparent non-enhancement of the subendocardium with enhancement of the remaining myocardium, just the opposite of what would be expected in cardiac amyloidosis. In this case, the enhancement pattern resulted from selection of an inappropriate inversion time, which caused nulling of signal from the abnormal subendocardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F3A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g03b.jpeg" height="1616" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3b.</b>  Cardiac amyloidosis in a 75-year-old man with multiple myeloma. Diffuse myocardial thickening and restrictive physiologic findings were seen at cardiac echocardiography. <b>(a)</b> Two-chamber short-axis true fast imaging with steady-state precession (FISP) image shows bilateral ventricular myocardial thickening. <b>(b, c)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced two-chamber short-axis cardiac MR images (<b>c</b> obtained slightly apical to <b>b</b>) show apparent non-enhancement of the subendocardium with enhancement of the remaining myocardium, just the opposite of what would be expected in cardiac amyloidosis. In this case, the enhancement pattern resulted from selection of an inappropriate inversion time, which caused nulling of signal from the abnormal subendocardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F3B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g03c.jpeg" height="1557" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3c.</b>  Cardiac amyloidosis in a 75-year-old man with multiple myeloma. Diffuse myocardial thickening and restrictive physiologic findings were seen at cardiac echocardiography. <b>(a)</b> Two-chamber short-axis true fast imaging with steady-state precession (FISP) image shows bilateral ventricular myocardial thickening. <b>(b, c)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced two-chamber short-axis cardiac MR images (<b>c</b> obtained slightly apical to <b>b</b>) show apparent non-enhancement of the subendocardium with enhancement of the remaining myocardium, just the opposite of what would be expected in cardiac amyloidosis. In this case, the enhancement pattern resulted from selection of an inappropriate inversion time, which caused nulling of signal from the abnormal subendocardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F3C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g04a.jpeg" height="1754" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  Eosinophilic endomyocarditis in a 57-year-old man who presented with dyspnea. Thrombus was seen in the left ventricular apex at echocardiography. Delayed contrast-enhanced four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and two-chamber <b>(b)</b> long-axis cardiac MR images show thin subendocardial enhancement in a nonvascular distribution (arrows) as well as a large apical thrombus (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). The patient was found to have a markedly elevated absolute eosinophil count, leading to a diagnosis of hypereosinophilic syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g04b.jpeg" height="1562" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  Eosinophilic endomyocarditis in a 57-year-old man who presented with dyspnea. Thrombus was seen in the left ventricular apex at echocardiography. Delayed contrast-enhanced four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and two-chamber <b>(b)</b> long-axis cardiac MR images show thin subendocardial enhancement in a nonvascular distribution (arrows) as well as a large apical thrombus (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). The patient was found to have a markedly elevated absolute eosinophil count, leading to a diagnosis of hypereosinophilic syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g05a.jpeg" height="1713" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  Histiocytoid cardiomyopathy in a 7-month-old girl who presented with recurrent ventricular tachyarrhythmias. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis single-shot true FISP images obtained from the base <b>(a)</b> toward the apex <b>(c)</b> show multiple enhancing nodules (arrow) involving the subendocardium of the septal, inferior, and lateral walls. Transcatheter myocardial biopsy revealed histiocytoid myocytes consistent with histiocytoid cardiomyopathy. The patient subsequently underwent cardiac transplantation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g05b.jpeg" height="1750" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  Histiocytoid cardiomyopathy in a 7-month-old girl who presented with recurrent ventricular tachyarrhythmias. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis single-shot true FISP images obtained from the base <b>(a)</b> toward the apex <b>(c)</b> show multiple enhancing nodules (arrow) involving the subendocardium of the septal, inferior, and lateral walls. Transcatheter myocardial biopsy revealed histiocytoid myocytes consistent with histiocytoid cardiomyopathy. The patient subsequently underwent cardiac transplantation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g05c.jpeg" height="1739" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5c.</b>  Histiocytoid cardiomyopathy in a 7-month-old girl who presented with recurrent ventricular tachyarrhythmias. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis single-shot true FISP images obtained from the base <b>(a)</b> toward the apex <b>(c)</b> show multiple enhancing nodules (arrow) involving the subendocardium of the septal, inferior, and lateral walls. Transcatheter myocardial biopsy revealed histiocytoid myocytes consistent with histiocytoid cardiomyopathy. The patient subsequently underwent cardiac transplantation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F5C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g06a.jpeg" height="1486" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6a.</b>  Transmural infarction in a 54-year-old man with antiphospholipid antibody syndrome and embolic infarcts in the setting of a left ventricular thrombus. The patient had undergone left ventricular thrombectomy and presented for follow-up evaluation. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis cardiac MR images (<b>b</b> slightly apical to <b>a</b>) show transmural enhancement in the anterior wall of the left ventricle (arrow), a finding that is consistent with transmural infarction of the left anterior descending coronary artery territory.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F6A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g06b.jpeg" height="1488" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6b.</b>  Transmural infarction in a 54-year-old man with antiphospholipid antibody syndrome and embolic infarcts in the setting of a left ventricular thrombus. The patient had undergone left ventricular thrombectomy and presented for follow-up evaluation. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis cardiac MR images (<b>b</b> slightly apical to <b>a</b>) show transmural enhancement in the anterior wall of the left ventricle (arrow), a finding that is consistent with transmural infarction of the left anterior descending coronary artery territory.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F6B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g07a.jpeg" height="1432" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7a.</b>  Transmural infarction in a 60-year-old man with thrombosis of a proximal left anterior descending coronary artery stent that had been placed 2 years earlier. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis cardiac MR images (<b>b</b> slightly apical to <b>a</b>) show transmural enhancement in the anterior wall of the left ventricle (arrows) with extension into the anteroseptal and anterolateral walls, findings that are consistent with transmural infarction of the left anterior descending coronary artery territory.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F7A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g07b.jpeg" height="1444" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7b.</b>  Transmural infarction in a 60-year-old man with thrombosis of a proximal left anterior descending coronary artery stent that had been placed 2 years earlier. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis cardiac MR images (<b>b</b> slightly apical to <b>a</b>) show transmural enhancement in the anterior wall of the left ventricle (arrows) with extension into the anteroseptal and anterolateral walls, findings that are consistent with transmural infarction of the left anterior descending coronary artery territory.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F7B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g08a.jpeg" height="1502" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8a.</b>  Transmural infarction in a 70-year-old man with atherosclerotic coronary disease and high- grade right coronary artery stenosis. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis cardiac MR images (<b>b</b> slightly apical to <b>a</b>) show transmural enhancement in the inferior and inferoseptal walls of the left ventricle (arrow), a finding that is consistent with transmural infarction of the right coronary artery territory.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F8A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g08b.jpeg" height="1486" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8b.</b>  Transmural infarction in a 70-year-old man with atherosclerotic coronary disease and high- grade right coronary artery stenosis. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis cardiac MR images (<b>b</b> slightly apical to <b>a</b>) show transmural enhancement in the inferior and inferoseptal walls of the left ventricle (arrow), a finding that is consistent with transmural infarction of the right coronary artery territory.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F8B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g09x.jpeg" height="1308" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9.</b>  Viral myocarditis in a 23-year-old man who presented with chest pain 1 week after contracting an upper respiratory infection. Delayed contrast-enhanced four-chamber long-axis cardiac MR image shows diffuse subepicardial enhancement (arrows). Viral titers were positive for Coxsackie viral infection, and a diagnosis of viral myocarditis was made.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g10a.jpeg" height="1657" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10a.</b>  Autoimmune myocarditis in a 54-year-old man with newly diagnosed polymyositis. The patient presented initially with myalgias and muscle weakness and was subsequently found to have congestive heart failure. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis <b>(a–c)</b> and two-chamber long-axis <b>(d)</b> cardiac MR images show diffuse subepicardial enhancement (arrows) extending to involve the septal mesocardium. A small pericardial effusion is also noted (arrowhead in <b>a</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F10A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g10b.jpeg" height="1671" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10b.</b>  Autoimmune myocarditis in a 54-year-old man with newly diagnosed polymyositis. The patient presented initially with myalgias and muscle weakness and was subsequently found to have congestive heart failure. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis <b>(a–c)</b> and two-chamber long-axis <b>(d)</b> cardiac MR images show diffuse subepicardial enhancement (arrows) extending to involve the septal mesocardium. A small pericardial effusion is also noted (arrowhead in <b>a</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F10B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g10c.jpeg" height="1586" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10c.</b>  Autoimmune myocarditis in a 54-year-old man with newly diagnosed polymyositis. The patient presented initially with myalgias and muscle weakness and was subsequently found to have congestive heart failure. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis <b>(a–c)</b> and two-chamber long-axis <b>(d)</b> cardiac MR images show diffuse subepicardial enhancement (arrows) extending to involve the septal mesocardium. A small pericardial effusion is also noted (arrowhead in <b>a</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F10C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g10d.jpeg" height="1800" width="1695" aria-labelledby="F10D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10d.</b>  Autoimmune myocarditis in a 54-year-old man with newly diagnosed polymyositis. The patient presented initially with myalgias and muscle weakness and was subsequently found to have congestive heart failure. Delayed contrast-enhanced short-axis <b>(a–c)</b> and two-chamber long-axis <b>(d)</b> cardiac MR images show diffuse subepicardial enhancement (arrows) extending to involve the septal mesocardium. A small pericardial effusion is also noted (arrowhead in <b>a</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F10D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g11a.jpeg" height="1573" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Lupus myocarditis in a 47-year-old woman with newly diagnosed systemic lupus erythematosus who presented with dyspnea. Delayed contrast-enhanced two-chamber short-axis <b>(a)</b> and four-chamber long-axis <b>(b)</b> cardiac MR images show patchy subepicardial enhancement in the lateral wall of the left ventricle (arrow in <b>a</b>) and a large pericardial effusion (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g11b.jpeg" height="1592" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Lupus myocarditis in a 47-year-old woman with newly diagnosed systemic lupus erythematosus who presented with dyspnea. Delayed contrast-enhanced two-chamber short-axis <b>(a)</b> and four-chamber long-axis <b>(b)</b> cardiac MR images show patchy subepicardial enhancement in the lateral wall of the left ventricle (arrow in <b>a</b>) and a large pericardial effusion (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g12a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1732" aria-labelledby="F12A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12a.</b>  Septal hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in a 27-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber long-axis true FISP image shows focal hypertrophy of the interventricular septum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced image obtained in the same plane reveals enhancement within the hypertrophic septum (arrow), a finding that is thought to represent fibrosis. (Case courtesy of Arthur Stillman, MD, Emory University.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F12A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g12b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1706" aria-labelledby="F12B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12b.</b>  Septal hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in a 27-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber long-axis true FISP image shows focal hypertrophy of the interventricular septum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced image obtained in the same plane reveals enhancement within the hypertrophic septum (arrow), a finding that is thought to represent fibrosis. (Case courtesy of Arthur Stillman, MD, Emory University.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F12B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g13a.jpeg" height="1759" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13a.</b>  Dilated cardiomyopathy in a 34-year-old man who presented with progressive dyspnea. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber long-axis true FISP image shows marked enlargement of the left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced cardiac MR image obtained in the same plane reveals isolated mesocardial enhancement within the interventricular septum (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F13A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g13b.jpeg" height="1719" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13b.</b>  Dilated cardiomyopathy in a 34-year-old man who presented with progressive dyspnea. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber long-axis true FISP image shows marked enlargement of the left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced cardiac MR image obtained in the same plane reveals isolated mesocardial enhancement within the interventricular septum (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F13B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g14a.jpeg" height="1742" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F14A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14a.</b>  Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 65-year-old woman with extensive pulmonary sarcoidosis in whom echocardiography had revealed diffuse myocardial thickening. Delayed contrast-enhanced two-chamber short-axis <b>(a)</b> and two-chamber long-axis <b>(b)</b> cardiac MR images show nodular areas of enhancement within the basal inferior wall (arrow), along with myocardial thinning.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F14A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g14b.jpeg" height="1744" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F14B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14b.</b>  Cardiac sarcoidosis in a 65-year-old woman with extensive pulmonary sarcoidosis in whom echocardiography had revealed diffuse myocardial thickening. Delayed contrast-enhanced two-chamber short-axis <b>(a)</b> and two-chamber long-axis <b>(b)</b> cardiac MR images show nodular areas of enhancement within the basal inferior wall (arrow), along with myocardial thinning.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F14B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g15a.jpeg" height="1688" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F15A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15a.</b>  Myocardial noncompaction in a 27-year-old woman who presented with severe congestive heart failure. <b>(a)</b> Two-chamber short-axis cardiac MR image shows increased trabeculation (arrow) and deep intertrabecular grooves in the lateral wall of the left ventricle, findings that are suggestive of noncompaction. <b>(b)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced cardiac MR image obtained in the same plane shows diffuse enhancement within the area of myocardial noncompaction (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F15A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g15b.jpeg" height="1670" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F15B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15b.</b>  Myocardial noncompaction in a 27-year-old woman who presented with severe congestive heart failure. <b>(a)</b> Two-chamber short-axis cardiac MR image shows increased trabeculation (arrow) and deep intertrabecular grooves in the lateral wall of the left ventricle, findings that are suggestive of noncompaction. <b>(b)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced cardiac MR image obtained in the same plane shows diffuse enhancement within the area of myocardial noncompaction (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F15B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g16a.jpeg" height="1711" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F16A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16a.</b>  Transient left ventricular apical ballooning syndrome (takotsubo cardiomyopathy) in a 42-year-old woman who developed sudden onset of dyspnea and angina. The patient had a mildly elevated troponin level and ST segment elevations at electrocardiography, but conventional coronary angiographic findings were normal. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber long-axis true FISP cardiac MR image shows dilatation or ballooning of the apex with sparing of the base. At cine MR imaging, the base was noted to be hyperdynamic with apical dyskinesis. <b>(b)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced cardiac MR image obtained in the same plane reveals no areas of abnormal enhancement that would suggest an ischemic cause. The patient recovered fully with supportive measures.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F16A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g16b.jpeg" height="1685" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F16B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16b.</b>  Transient left ventricular apical ballooning syndrome (takotsubo cardiomyopathy) in a 42-year-old woman who developed sudden onset of dyspnea and angina. The patient had a mildly elevated troponin level and ST segment elevations at electrocardiography, but conventional coronary angiographic findings were normal. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber long-axis true FISP cardiac MR image shows dilatation or ballooning of the apex with sparing of the base. At cine MR imaging, the base was noted to be hyperdynamic with apical dyskinesis. <b>(b)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced cardiac MR image obtained in the same plane reveals no areas of abnormal enhancement that would suggest an ischemic cause. The patient recovered fully with supportive measures.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F16B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085052/asset/images/g09ja05g17x.jpeg" height="889" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17.</b>  Chart illustrates the differential diagnosis of delayed contrast enhancement at cardiac MR imaging by location.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085052&amp;id=F17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Borchert</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">B</span></span>, Lawrenz T, Bartelsmeier M, Rothemeyer S, Kuhn H, Stellbrink C. Utility of endomyocardial biopsy guided by delayed enhancement areas on magnetic resonance imaging in the diagnosis of cardiac sarcoidosis. <em>Clin Res Cardiol</em>2007; 96(10): 759–762.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00392-007-0557-1">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17694383/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Clin+Res+Cardiol&amp;publication_year=2007&amp;pages=759&amp;doi=10.1007%2Fs00392-007-0557-1&amp;pmid=17694383">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="R2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Vogelsberg</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">H</span></span>, Mahrholdt H, Deluigi C, et al. Cardiovascular magnetic resonance in clinically suspected cardiac amyloidosis: noninvasive imaging compared to endomyocardial biopsy. <em>J Am Coll Cardiol</em>2008; 51(10): 1022–1030.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-cros